{{Infobox religious building | name = {{Nihongo|Kumano Nachi Taisha|熊野那智大社}} | image = Kumano-Nachi-shrine002.JPG | caption = Kumano Nachi Taisha's ''[[Heiden (Shinto)|heiden]]'' | map_type = Japan | map_alt = | coordinates = {{coord|33|40|07|N|135|53|26|E|display=title,inline|region:JP_type:landmark_source:dewiki}} | map_relief = | map_size = | map_caption = | religious_affiliation = [[Shinto]] | type = | deity = Fusumi no kami (Izanami no mikoto) and others<ref>Cali, Joseph. Shinto Shrines: A Guide to the Sacred Sites of Japan's Ancient Religion. — Honolulu, 2013. — pp. 253-256.</ref> | founded_by = | established = | date_destroyed = | location = [[Nachikatsuura]], [[Higashimuro District, Wakayama|Higashimuro District]], [[Wakayama Prefecture]], [[Japan]] | website = | architecture_style = | festival = | leadership = }}
{{Nihongo|'''Kumano Nachi Taisha'''|熊野那智大社}} is a [[Shinto shrine]] and part of the [[UNESCO]]-designated [[World Heritage]] [[Sacred Sites and Pilgrimage Routes in the Kii Mountain Range]] of [[Japan]]. The [[Kumano Kodō]] route connects it to other sites under the same classification, which are primarily located in [[Wakayama Prefecture]], Japan. The four sites on the route, classified as pilgrimage destinations and World Heritage Sites, are: 1) Nachi Taisha; 2) [[Kumano Hongū Taisha|Hongū Taisha]]; 3) [[Kumano Hayatama Taisha|Hayatama Taisha]]; 4) [[Mount Kōya|Koya-san]].
Kumano Nachi Taisha is also one of the three sacred [[Kumano Shrine|Kumano Sanzan]] shrines: # Kumano Nachi Taisha # [[Kumano Hongū Taisha]] # [[Kumano Hayatama Taisha]] This classification is based mostly in Japanese history, as pilgrims would travel to all three sites to complete their pilgrimage.
Kumano Nachi Taisha is an example of Buddhist and Shinto [[syncretism]] ([[Shinbutsu shūgō]]) nestled in the Kii Mountains, near Kii Katsuura, Japan. Cedar forests surround the site. The 133-meter [[Nachi Falls|Nachi Waterfall]], worshiped at the Hiryū Shrine near Kumano Nachi Taisha, is believed to be inhabited by a ''[[kami]]'' called Hiryū [[Gongen]].<ref name="nachi">{{cite web|url=http://www.kkr.mlit.go.jp/wakayama/rekishi/disco131.html|title=Hiryū Gongen|last=Kamizaka|first=Jirō|publisher=Ministry of Land, Infrastructure and Transport - Kinki Regional Development Bureau|language=ja|access-date=28 March 2010}}</ref> Also, there is a sacred tree at this site, the Sacred [[Camphor laurel|Camphor Tree]], located between the Nachi Shrine (''[[Heiden (Shinto)|heiden]]'') and [[Seiganto-ji|Seigantoji temple]]. It is 850 years old and is said to have been planted by [[Taira no Shigemori|Taira-no-Shigemori]] (1138-1179). The straw rope (''[[shimenawa]]'') and paper flags show that this tree has been sanctified as a ''kami''. The tree is alive with moss and ferns and other small plants growing on its ancient limbs. It is possible to enter the base of the tree, where there is a small altar for making offerings, and come out above ground level.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://sacredjapan.com/Temple%2001/Nachi%20Taisha.htm|title = Nachi Taisha-Sacred Camphor Tree|access-date = October 9, 2014|website = Sacred Japan|last = Juno|first = Cate Kodo|archive-date = March 3, 2016|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160303212124/http://sacredjapan.com/Temple%2001/Nachi%20Taisha.htm|url-status = dead}}</ref>
Nachi-no-Hi Matsuri Fire Festival, performed on [[July 14]], is the major festival of Kumano Nachi Taisha. It is a fire festival in which six-meter-high portable shrines symbolically representing the purification of the waterfall with the fires from oversized torches is laboriously carried by men dressed in white.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.tb-kumano.jp/en/world-heritage/kumano-nachi-taisha/|title = Kumano Nachi Taisha 熊野那智大社|access-date = October 9, 2014|website = Sacred Kumano|publisher = Tanabe City Kumano Tourism Bureau}}</ref>
